    contentEn: 
`<h2>Why is a Mistake Made in Curtain Selection?</h2>
<p>Curtains are one of the most important parts of home decoration; but most of the time the selection process is rushed. Users sometimes decide by looking only at the color or model. However, curtain selection should be evaluated together with measurement, fabric, room use, light status, privacy needs, and installation method.</p>
<p>The wrong curtain selection can create dissatisfaction in terms of both aesthetics and use. Therefore, knowing the common mistakes when buying curtains makes it easier to make the right decision.</p>

<h2>Choosing Based Only on Appearance</h2>
<p>One of the most common mistakes is focusing only on the curtain looking beautiful. A curtain can look very stylish in a store or catalog; but it may not be compatible with the light, furniture, and window measurements of the home.</p>
<p>When choosing curtains, functionality should be considered as much as visuality. For example, a very thin sheer curtain in the bedroom may not provide sufficient privacy. A heavy fabric drape curtain in the kitchen can be impractical.</p>

<h2>Taking Incorrect Measurements</h2>
<p>Curtain measurement errors are one of the most common problems. Taking only the glass measurement is usually not enough. How the curtain will cover the window, mounting location, side allowances, and height should be carefully determined.</p>
<p>Especially in roller, zebra, pleated, and venetian blinds, measurement errors can prevent the mechanism from working correctly.</p>

<h2>Not Considering the Light Status of the Room</h2>
<p>Choosing dark and thick curtains for a poorly lit room can make the space look darker. Choosing thin and insufficient curtains for a very sunny room can reduce comfort.</p>
<p>Before choosing curtains, which cephe the room faces, how much sun it receives during the day, and light needs should be evaluated.</p>

<h2>Choosing the Wrong Fabric Type</h2>
<p>Every fabric is not suitable for every room. Velvet curtains can be impractical in the kitchen. Very thin sheer curtains in the bedroom may not provide privacy. Blackout fabric can be too darkening for the living room.</p>
<p>Fabric selection should be made according to the purpose of use.</p>

<h2>Color Incompatibility</h2>
<p>When choosing curtain colors, wall, sofa, carpet, floor, and accessories should be considered together. All parts do not need to be the same color; but there should be harmony or conscious contrast between colors.</p>
<p>Using highly patterned curtains with highly patterned furniture can create visual clutter. For balance, one side should be kept plain.</p>

<h2>Seeing Installation as Unimportant</h2>
<p>If a quality curtain is installed incorrectly, it does not hang properly and becomes difficult to use. In cornice, rustic, roller, or zebra blind installation, robustness and alignment are important. Crooked installation in mechanized curtains can cause fabric shifting.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>Mistakes made when buying curtains generally stem from not thinking enough about measurement, fabric, color, room needs, and installation details. Getting professional support for correct curtain selection yields better results in the long run. Lale Perde helps users to choose the most suitable curtains for their living spaces with measuring, fabric selection, and installation support.</p>
`,
